            <p>Philadelphia March 7<hi rend="sup">th</hi> 1852.<lb/></p>
                <p>Mr Tinze.<lb/>
                Secretary of the Hebrew Education Society<lb/>
                Sir.<lb/></p>
                <p>I have received your letter dated Feb 15th<lb/> informing me of my re&#45;election as Assistant Teacher for<lb/> the ensuing year&#44; but as no request was made therein for<lb/> a reply&#44; I did not deem it requisite that one was <del>required</del> expected<lb/> which office I shall be pleased to accept.  On this day&#44;<lb/> I received another&#44; together with a resolution directing<lb/> me in addition to my regular duties&#44; to become an<lb/> Assistant Hebrew Teacher&#44; this in consequence of the<lb/> large number of scholars in my class requiring all<lb/> my time and attention&#44; and believing that my<lb/> knowledge of Hebrew insufficient I must in consequence&#44;<lb/> request you to inform the Board of Directors&#44; that<lb/> it will be impossible for me to comply with the<lb/> request contained in the last resolution.<lb/></p>
                <p>I remain yours<lb/>
                respectfully<lb/>
                Clara E Weil.<lb/>
            </p>
            
        </body>
    </text>
